Vheadline
p2
VRemembering a legend
p3
sVnews
p4
VVinjamuri Varadaraja Iyengar was a musician, musicologist, composer and a vocalist of considerable talent. He hailed from a musical family based in Guntur. His guru Piratla Sankara Sastry was from the Veena Kuppaier School and also had the tutelage under Tiger Varadachariar, also from the Kuppaier school.In fact, earlier he used to be fondly called &#8216;Kutty Tiger&#8217; after Varadachari, as he adhered to his guru&#8217;s style, and also as &#8216;Andhra Ariyakudi&#8217; because of the influence of Ariyakudi&#8217;s style. He had a rare collection of musical instruments, particularly tanpuras given to him by his elders. He was well versed in Hindustani music too.He had written extensively on musicians both in Telugu and English. He composedtana varnams, krities,javaliesandtillanas. He set music to Andal&#8217;sTiruppavaiand Lakshmi Narasimhastotram.  He became the principal of Central School for Music and Dance in 1952, at the behest of the then chief minister Burgula Ramakrishna Rao. He was in the post for an year and then became a producer in AIR, Hyderabad.He introduced programmes likeBhakti Ranjani, Sangeetha Sikshana, Vadya Brundamwhosetradition continues even now, with other stations of AIR also taking up this cause of music. He passed away in the year 1991. The South Indian Cultural Association of Hyderabad has been celebrating his memory for a long time now by holding two exclusive concerts, every year. This year, it was held in October at Ravindra Bharati.
